1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,919
Does communism change your mind? It's a strong question, almost a provocation.

2
00:00:04,919 --> 00:00:09,839
Yet, the incredible thing is that, thanks to a very recent piece of history, we can

3
00:00:09,839 --> 00:00:12,919
try to answer it in a surprisingly scientific way.

4
00:00:12,919 --> 00:00:15,120
So, let's get into it.

5
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:21,000
Can a political system come to shape our way of thinking? Can it really influence

6
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,839
our most deep-seated beliefs, those about the role of the state, the market, and

7
00:00:25,839 --> 00:00:30,600
society? For decades, this was an almost impossible question for social

8
00:00:30,600 --> 00:00:35,679
scientists. How, after all, do you isolate the effect of a political system from everything else—

9
00:00:35,679 --> 00:00:41,439
culture, history, the economy? Well, almost impossible, until history itself

10
00:00:41,439 --> 00:00:43,640
provided us with a unique opportunity.

11
00:00:43,640 --> 00:00:49,719
And this opportunity has a very specific name: it's a natural experiment, and the laboratory for

12
00:00:49,719 --> 00:00:55,039
this experiment was Germany, right after the Second World War—a historical case

13
00:00:55,039 --> 00:00:58,960
that seems almost designed on purpose to answer our question.

14
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:01,799
But what exactly is a natural experiment?

15
00:01:01,799 --> 00:01:07,239
Well, in simple terms, it's when history, by pure chance, does what a scientist

16
00:01:07,239 --> 00:01:12,400
would do in a laboratory: it takes a homogeneous group of people, divides it in two, and applies a

17
00:01:12,400 --> 00:01:14,840
treatment to one half and not the other.

18
00:01:14,840 --> 00:01:19,719
In this case, the homogeneous group was the German people, and the external event was the division

19
00:01:19,719 --> 00:01:25,640
of the country: on one side, Communist East Germany, our treatment group; on the other,

20
00:01:25,640 --> 00:01:29,680
Capitalist West Germany, our control group.

21
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:30,680
Perfect.

22
00:01:30,680 --> 00:01:33,239
Let's look at the timeline, because it's fundamental.

23
00:01:33,239 --> 00:01:39,719
Before '45, there was only one nation, a shared culture; then for 45 very long years,

24
00:01:39,719 --> 00:01:46,960
from 1945 to 1990, these two parts lived under two radically opposite economic and political

25
00:01:46,960 --> 00:01:47,960
systems.

26
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:52,560
And with reunification, we can finally compare the results and see

27
00:01:52,560 --> 00:01:53,560
what happened.

28
00:01:53,560 --> 00:01:55,880
The crazy thing is this:

29
00:01:55,880 --> 00:02:00,400
before the division, the two Germanies were practically the same; historians

30
00:02:00,400 --> 00:02:04,360
say they had almost identical income levels, a similar industrial structure,

31
00:02:04,360 --> 00:02:07,600
and even very, very similar political and social attitudes.

32
00:02:07,600 --> 00:02:12,520
In short, the starting line was the same for everyone, and that's precisely what makes

33
00:02:12,520 --> 00:02:16,360
the comparison after 45 years so powerful and so revealing.

34
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:22,560
So, let's get to the point: what happened after the fall of the Wall? What differences

35
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:23,560
emerged?

36
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:29,760
It's here that we enter the heart of the analysis, the great clash of ideas between state and market.

37
00:02:29,760 --> 00:02:32,520
Let's look at the data; let's take a key question.

38
00:02:32,520 --> 00:02:37,920
In case of unemployment, who should guarantee economic security: the state or the individual?

39
00:02:37,920 --> 00:02:41,400
Well, the answers revealed a very clear split.

40
00:02:41,400 --> 00:02:45,439
Former East Germans show an overwhelming preference for strong state

41
00:02:45,439 --> 00:02:46,439
intervention.

42
00:02:46,439 --> 00:02:50,620
While in the West, there is a greater tendency to rely on private or

43
00:02:50,620 --> 00:02:51,620
individual solutions.

44
00:02:51,620 --> 00:02:57,120
And mind you, it's not an isolated case; this pattern is repeated practically everywhere.

45
00:02:57,120 --> 00:03:02,640
Let's talk about healthcare: same story. Elderly care: the same. Support for

46
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:08,640
families: ditto. A consistent model emerges: those who lived under the communist system

47
00:03:08,640 --> 00:03:12,800
tend to demand and trust state intervention much more.

48
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:14,400
Want a figure?

49
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:20,520
Here it is: data from 1997—so, almost a decade after reunification—tells us that

50
00:03:20,520 --> 00:03:26,960
a citizen of former East Germany was, on average, 16% more likely to

51
00:03:26,960 --> 00:03:33,240
want state intervention compared to a compatriot from the West. 16% is

52
00:03:33,240 --> 00:03:36,880
a gigantic gap if we consider they started from the same point.

53
00:03:37,359 --> 00:03:39,039
Okay, but why?

54
00:03:39,039 --> 00:03:41,960
Where does this deep difference come from?

55
00:03:41,960 --> 00:03:45,639
Is it simply because the East was economically weaker?

56
00:03:45,639 --> 00:03:50,359
Or is there something more to it, something to do with the mindset itself?

57
00:03:50,359 --> 00:03:54,359
Researchers asked exactly this question.

58
00:03:54,359 --> 00:03:59,319
Of course, East Germany was poorer, and usually those who have less tend to ask for more help

59
00:03:59,319 --> 00:04:00,439
from the state.

60
00:04:00,439 --> 00:04:05,519
But the interesting thing is that even after cleaning the data of these differences in

61
00:04:05,520 --> 00:04:13,120
income, wealth, or employment, the gap in opinions remained large and unequivocal.

62
00:04:13,120 --> 00:04:18,280
This suggests that it's not just a matter of the wallet; it's something deeper:

63
00:04:18,280 --> 00:04:21,360
a real change in how the world is viewed.

64
00:04:21,360 --> 00:04:24,720
And here is a clue that takes us straight to the point.

65
00:04:24,720 --> 00:04:29,160
Respondents were asked how much they agreed with this phrase—

66
00:04:29,160 --> 00:04:34,639
a phrase that is, in fact, a pillar of Marxist ideology: the idea that a person's fate

67
00:04:34,639 --> 00:04:40,000
depends not so much on individual effort, but on the conditions of the society

68
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:41,000
in which they live.

69
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:47,560
In fact, the results are clear: those who lived in the East believe much, much more firmly

70
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:48,560
in this idea.

71
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:54,639
And the reasoning at that point becomes almost automatic: if you believe that life is determined

72
00:04:54,639 --> 00:04:59,800
by social conditions, then it is logical and natural to ask the state—that is, the

73
00:04:59,800 --> 00:05:04,600
collectivity—to intervene to improve those conditions for everyone.

74
00:05:04,600 --> 00:05:09,439
The demand for state intervention, therefore, is nothing but the direct consequence of this

75
00:05:09,439 --> 00:05:10,439
mentality.

76
00:05:10,439 --> 00:05:16,199
And here comes the acid test, what in jargon is called the dose-response effect.

77
00:05:16,199 --> 00:05:22,000
The more years a person spent under the East German regime, the stronger their preference

78
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:23,000
for the state.

79
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:28,160
For younger people, those born after '75, who saw little to nothing of communism, the

80
00:05:28,160 --> 00:05:32,480
difference with their peers from the West is minimal, but as you go back in

81
00:05:32,480 --> 00:05:35,520
age, the gap becomes enormous, almost an abyss.

82
00:05:35,520 --> 00:05:40,120
This links the direct experience of that political system to the change in mentality in a

83
00:05:40,120 --> 00:05:42,720
way that is almost impossible to dispute.

84
00:05:42,720 --> 00:05:50,040
Fine, but is this psychological imprint, this mental wall, destined to fade? And if so,

85
00:05:50,040 --> 00:05:52,720
how long will it take to collapse completely?

86
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:56,000
The study's estimate is nothing short of staggering.

87
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:01,160
It talks about a period between 20 and 40 years—you heard that right, it will take one,

88
00:06:01,160 --> 00:06:05,600
perhaps even two generations, before the differences in mentality between East and West

89
00:06:05,600 --> 00:06:06,600
disappear.

90
00:06:06,600 --> 00:06:11,160
The echo of those 45 years of history is incredibly persistent.

91
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:17,360
And how will this slow reconciliation happen? Primarily through two paths.

92
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:22,600
For about two-thirds, it will depend on the fact that people living in the new unified system

93
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:24,000
will slowly change their minds.

94
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:28,879
But for the other third, the reason is much simpler, and a bit brutal: it is

95
00:06:28,879 --> 00:06:30,759
generational replacement.

96
00:06:30,759 --> 00:06:35,439
The older generations with more deep-seated ideas will give way to new ones,

97
00:06:35,439 --> 00:06:37,759
born and raised after reunification.

98
00:06:37,759 --> 00:06:42,399
Well, we are at the end of this journey through history and the mind.

99
00:06:42,399 --> 00:06:45,160
What does this whole story teach us?

100
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:48,360
What conclusions can we draw?

101
00:06:48,360 --> 00:06:53,680
Let's do a quick summary: first point, political systems are not empty boxes;

102
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:56,480
they can actively shape what we believe in.

103
00:06:56,480 --> 00:07:02,199
Second, 45 years of communism left a clear imprint—a greater demand

104
00:07:02,199 --> 00:07:06,780
for state intervention. Third and perhaps most importantly, it's not just about

105
00:07:06,780 --> 00:07:11,340
economics, but a real shift in mental paradigm. And finally, this

106
00:07:11,340 --> 00:07:16,079
psychological heritage dies hard, an echo that continues to resonate for decades.

107
00:07:16,079 --> 00:07:20,399
And all this leaves us with one final question to reflect on:

108
00:07:20,400 --> 00:07:26,040
if 45 years of a political system built such a solid, lasting mental wall,

109
00:07:26,040 --> 00:07:30,920
what other invisible walls, perhaps forged by our history, by our systems,

110
00:07:30,920 --> 00:07:35,520
might influence our way of thinking today, perhaps without us even noticing?